Development of strategies to identify and expand asset customers¶

Introduction¶

The AllLife Bank has had success in the last year in converting 9% of their liability customer base to asset customers. This has enabled the bank to generate additional revenue through interest on the loans. Based on this healthy conversion rate, it is useful to develop strategies to identify which of the liability customers are likely to become asset customers with the help of targeted marketing, while retaining them as liability customers also.

Background: The bank's liability customers are customers who have deposits in the bank and they are the largest group of customers for the bank. The asset customers are a small segment who borrow personal loans.

Objective¶

  1. Identifying liability customers who are likely to get a personal loan from the bank
  2. Generating insights into the characteristics of the customers that would put them in asset customer group

Data Information/Variables¶

ID - customer ID
Age - age of the customer (completed years)
Experience - number of years of professional service
Income - annual income of customer (in thousand dollars)
ZIPCode - zip code for home address
Family - the number of people in the household for the family
CCAvg - average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
Education - level of education (1. Undergrad, 2.Graduate, 3. Advanced/Professional)
Mortgage - Value of house mortgage (in thousand dollars)
Personal_Loan - Yes/No data in the form of 1/0, did the customer accept personal loan offered in last campaign
Securities_Account - Yes/No data in the form of 1/0, does customer have securities account in bank
CD_Account - Yes/No data in the form of 1/0, does customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) with the bank?
Online - Yes/No data in the form of 1/0, do customers use internet banking facilities?
CreditCard - Yes/No data in the form of 1/0, does customer use credit card issued by a bank that is not AllLife Bank?

Observations¶

  1. The mean and median for 'Age' is 45.33 years and 45 years approximately.This points to 'Age' variable being a symmetric distribution.The maximum age is 67 years, however 75% of the customers are between the age of 23-55 years. The range 23-55 years reflects mostly working professionals.
  2. The mean and median for 'Experience' variable is 20 years approximately. Thus, 'Experience' is also a symmertric distribution. The min for this variable is a value of "-3". While we expect number of years of professional service to be a positive number or 0, an entry of "-3" may be a value indicating the customer is a college freshman who will need 3 years to graduate.
  3. The mean and median for 'Income' are substantially different - 73,000 versus 64,000. This tells us that the distribution will be skewed.While the maximum value is 224,000 - 75% of the customers have an annual income of less than 98,000 dollars.
  4. The 'ZIPCode' column mean and median cannot be interpreted as they represent geographical residential areas. We can however see that they are all 5 digits.
  5. The mean and median for 'Family' is approximately 2 (meaning 2 people per household). This variable also will be a symmetric distribution. The maximum value is 4, while the minimum is close to 1 (so single person).
  6. 'CCAvg' is the average spending on credit cards per month, units is thousands of dollars. The mean is 1.93 approximately, and the median is 1.5 - a symmetric distribution. The min value is 0.0 and the max value is 10. The min value being 0 could indicate that the customer does not have a credit card, or that they do not use it.
  7. 'Education' has only 3 values between 1 and 3, hence the column can be treated like a categorical variable.
  8. 'Mortgage'has a mean of 56 approximately (56,000 dollars) but the median is 0. This indicates that the distribution is skewed, but moreover indicates that that the column might need some outlier treatment.
  9. 'Personal_Loan' is a Yes/No type - 0/1, so can be treated as a categorical column. The same holds true for 'Securities_Account','CD_Account','Online','CreditCard' columns.
  10. The dependent/target variable for the analysis is Personal_Loan.

Observations¶

  1. As we saw in the summary statistics, the mean and median for 'Income' variable were different - 73,000 versus 64,000 dollars. This indicates that the distribution is skewed, and is confirmed by the histogram plot above.
  2. The 'Income' distribution is skewed to the right (positive skew). The tail is to the right, so less number of customers have a higher income.
  3. The boxplot of 'Personal_Loan' versus 'Income' shows that high income earners (>100,000 dollars per annum) are the people, who in the previous marketing campaign, took a personal loan (a value of '1'). The median for the '1' group is significantly different than the median for the '0' group. While outliers are present in the '0' group, the two groups are significant different in their income groups.
  4. The high income earners and lower than 100,000 dollar income groups and whether they took a personal loan are unchanged by their education level. If the customers had an undergraduate degree, and if their income was less than 100,000 dollars, fewer numbers took a personal loan. However, customers who earned more than 100,000 dollars, they were more numbers who took a personal loan irrespective of whether they had an undergraduate degree, graduate degree or advanced/professional degree.
  5. A number of outliers are present for groups of customers who belong to household with 3 or 4 family members.
  6. There is no significant difference in the medians for customers who had a 'Securities_Account' or not, 'CD_Account' or not, whether they used online/mobile banking or not. The same holds for customers who had a credit card that did not belong to AllLife Bank.
  7. Outliers are present in 'Securities_Account','CD_Account','Online','CreditCard'.

In [38]:
# The functions below are for treating outliers
# First function is for treating a single column
def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """This function treats the outliers by putting all the values greater than the upper whisker
    to be equal to the value of the upper whisker (1.5*IQR)."""
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


# Function below is to treat a list of columns
def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    """This function uses the treat_outliers function and applies it to a list of columns"""
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c)

    return df

8. Logistic Regression Model¶

This section has the following subsections:

  1. Creating the training and testing data
  2. Building the logistic regression model
  3. Performance metrics for the logistic regression model
  4. Improvement of the logistic regression model

Note about model predictions¶

The Personal_Loan is the dependent variable. What we are trying to predict with the logistic regression model is that which of the customers in the data set are likely to take out a personal loan with the bank. That is we are trying to predict which of the customers from the test data set will have Personal_loan = 1 or Personal_loan = 0.

We will use recall and F1 as our most important performance measures.

The wrong predictions will consist of (a) the customer was predicted to take out a personal loan, but did not when the marketing campaign targeted that customer (False Positive) and (b) the customer was predicted to not take a personal loan, but ended up taking a personal loan with the bank (False Negative).

In terms of cost and resources, the false positives (predicted for personal_loan = 1) will be more concerning because the marketing campaign will cost money and resources, and predictions will tie into revenue predictions/strategies as well.

Hence, the model analysis must reduce the occurances of false positives.

We will not focus on accuracy as a performance measure because we know beforehand that the data is not balanced data.

Recall, which is the true positivity rate and precision, which is the specificity/true negative rate are both important and maximzing F1 such that neither recall nor precision suffers, will be the aim.

# Function to calculate performance metrics for classification models
# threshold = 0.5 for this function
def model_performance_classification_sklearn_with_threshold(
    model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5
):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics, based on the threshold specified, to check classification model performance
    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred_thres = pred_prob > threshold
    pred = np.round(pred_thres)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [44]:
# Function to create the confusion matrix
def confusion_matrix_sklearn_with_threshold(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix, based on the threshold specified, with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred_thres = pred_prob > threshold
    y_pred = np.round(pred_thres)

    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

In [54]:
# For improvement of the model, we will calculate the threshold using AUC-ROC strategy
# Optimal threshold as per AUC-ROC curve
# The optimal cut off would be where tpr is high and fpr is low
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, lg.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1])

optimal_idx = np.argmax(tpr - fpr)
optimal_threshold_auc_roc = thresholds[optimal_idx]
print(optimal_threshold_auc_roc)

0.13716269004907247

Observations¶

Using the area under the curve for the ROC curve, such that the true positivity rate will remain high, while the false positivity rate will remain low, the threshold is found to be 0.137.

# We will attempt the Precision-Recall curve to find a better threshold
y_scores = lg.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
prec, rec, tre = precision_recall_curve(
    y_train,
    y_scores,
)


def plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], "b--", label="precision")
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], "g--", label="recall")
    plt.xlabel("Threshold")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
    plt.ylim([0, 1])


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(prec, rec, tre)
plt.show()

Observations¶

From above, we can observe that at higher thresholds, the recall dips. While at higher thresholds, the precision improves. We will use a threshold - say 0.35 - to get a balance between the recall and the precision. This will help us get a reasonable F1 score.

Observations¶

  1. We will ignore the accuracy measure here - because it is an imbalanced data set - because 90% of the data is Personal_Loan = 0, the model will end up having accuracy of approximately 90% even if it predicts every single customer has Personal_Loan = 0.
  2. There is one instance where the recall is greater than 80% - it is for the model that used area under the curve for ROC curve to decide a threshold. The recall is the true positivity rate/sensitivity so 88% is a good value for recall.For a threshold of 0.5, and for 9 features, the recall drops to 63%.
  3. The precision is above 80% twice - for a threshold of 0.5, and for features used = 9.The precision is the true negativity rate/specificity so ideally we would like precision to be high.
  4. The F1 score - which is based on recall as well as precision but can be pulled down by either having a low score - is highest (74.8%) when the precision-recall curve is used to estimate a threshold.
  5. To decide which model is most reasonable in terms of performance, and keeping in mind, that we want to reduce false positives - the model where the threshold is 0.35 (chosen based on precision-recall curves) such that recall and precision and F1 that are close to each other and approximately 75%.
  6. The false positives = 2.31% and false negatives = 2.51% for the training data when the threshold is 0.35.

##  Function to calculate accuracy, recall, precision and F1 (no threshold)
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable

    """
    pred = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [84]:
# We will use a function for confusion matrix which does not use a threshold
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Note: Our next approach to improve the decision tree model will be to tune the hyperparameters. Hyperparameters are specified before the algorithm starts. For this analysis, GridSearchCV, which uses cross validation, will be used for hyperparameter tuning.

In [130]:
# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, class_weight={0: 0.10, 1: 0.9})

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": [5, 10, 15, None],
    "criterion": ["entropy", "gini"],
    "splitter": ["best", "random"],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.00001, 0.0001, 0.01],
}

# We will use recall as the scoring mechanism for perfomance metric
scorer = make_scorer(recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

In [109]:
##  Function to calculate accuracy, recall, precision and F1 (no threshold)
def model_performance_classification_sklearn1(model, predictors, target):
    """
    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable

    """
    pred = model.predict(predictors)
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Observation¶

We can see the decision tree with hyperparameters that are tuned has a lot less levels than the default decision tree.

If the income of the customer is less than or equal to 92,500 dollars per annum, and the CCAvg is less than 2.95 thousand dollars per month, then the customer is unlikely to take a personal loan from the bank. The other branches can be interpreted similarly.

However, if the income of the customer is less than or equal to 92,500 and the CCAvg is greater than 2.95, then the customer is in class 1 (which is Personal_Loan = 1, which indicates that customer will take a personal loan from the bank).

Observation¶

The best model to pick would be the first decision tree model (default depth) based on its testing performance (Recall = 88% and F1 = 93.9%). If we were to use only a recall score (we are interested in as high a true positivity rate as possible), then the best model would be the post pruned tree model with a recall of 100% and an F1 score of 77.1%. However, this model even though it had a high recall score, it would not prevent the occurance of false positives (the recall formula has false negatives in the denominator). As false positives will more costly to the bank in terms of resources, time (spending time and money in targeting a customer who does not take a loan), it is appropriate to pick the decision tree with the default depth.

10. Insights and Recommendations¶

Insights¶

  1. The average median of the customer base for AllLife bank is 45 years - so mostly middle aged customers. Since these are mostly liability customers who have deposits in the bank, the average age being middle aged indicates that the customers have a steady source of income or considerable income (as compared to a younger customer who may have just graduated from college.
  2. Majority of the customers have an undergraduate degree. Overall, all customers are educated.
  3. Approximately 75% of teh customers have an annunal income less than 100,000 dollars. Most of these customers did not take a personal loan in the previous marketing campaign. This means that (a) they did not have the resources to take a personal loan with the interest offered by the bank or (b) they did not need a personal loan or (c) the marketing campaign from last year was specifically geared towards high income earners and hence did not appeal to the less than 100,000 dollars per annum group.
  4. In terms of model performance, the decision tree models outperformed the logistic regression tree models, especially in the recall performance measure.
  5. Important characteristics of customers for marketing campaign are: income, education, family, and the average amount of money spent on credit cards in a month.
  6. Some counties are more important than others - for example, Los Angelos and Santa Clara county as shown by the analysis (based on correlation and feature importance).

Recommendations¶

  1. In order to have a higher conversion rate of liability customers to asset customers, the bank should develop a personal loan product that can appeal to the 75% of customers who earn less than 100,000 dollars per year.
  2. Income is one of the good predictors of whether the customer will take a personal loan or not, so the marketing campaign should continue to target high income earners with products that were similar to what was offered last year.
  3. The models showed that family is also an important factor - the more the number of people in the household, larger their annunal income, and more likely that they would be taking a personal loan. Based on this, the marketing department should target multiple products that can appeal to multiple people household - college loans as an example.
